revision.text:
{{current election|date=November 2018}} {{Politics of Bahrain}}
'''General elections''' were held in [[Bahrain]] on 24 November 2018,<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-bahrain-election/bahrain-to-hold-parliamentary-elections-on-nov-24-state-news-agency-idUKKCN1LQ21X|title=Bahrain to hold parliamentary elections on Nov. 24 - state news agency|date=10 September 2018|work=Reuters|access-date=5 October 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref> with a second round in some constituencies on 1 December.<ref name=TN>[https://www.thenational.ae/world/gcc/bahrain-announces-election-results-as-palace-prepares-for-visit-from-saudi-crown-prince-1.795639 Bahrain announces election results as palace prepares for visit from Saudi crown prince] The National, 25 November 2018</ref> Considered by some to be sham elections,<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/global-opinions/wp/2018/11/22/after-khashoggis-murder-its-time-for-the-world-to-stop-ignoring-bahrains-abuses/ After Khashoggi’s murder, it’s time for the world to stop ignoring Bahrain’s abuses] The New York Times, 22 November 2018</ref> they followed a crackdown on dissent that included prohibiting members of dissolved opposition groups from running.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.adhrb.org/2018/05/bahrain-moves-to-ban-opposition-ahead-of-2018-elections/|title=Bahrain Moves to Ban Opposition Ahead of 2018 Elections|last=|first=|date=30 May 2018|work=Americans for Democracy & Human Rights in Bahrain|access-date=5 October 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>
==Electoral system== The 40 members of the [[Council of Representatives (Bahrain)|Council of Representatives]] are elected from single-member constituencies using a [[two-round system]]; if no candidate receives a majority of the vote in the first round, a second round is held.<ref>[http://archive.ipu.org/parline-e/reports/2371_B.htm Electoral system] IPU</ref> Candidates had to apply between 17 and 21 October 2018,<ref name=":0" /> with 293 registering to contest the 40 seats.<ref>[https://gulfnews.com/world/gulf/bahrain/bahrain-poll-results-expected-today-1.60563311 Bahrain poll results expected today] Gulf News, 25 November 2018</ref>
==Results== Nine of the 40 constituencies had a winner in the first round, with the other 31 going to a runoff.<ref>[http://www.gdnonline.com/Details/442775/Run-off-for-31-seats-after-first-round-of-Bahrains-elections Run-off for 31 seats after first round of Bahrain's elections] GDN Online, 26 November 2018</ref> According to the regime, voter turnout in the first round was 67%, an increase from 53% in the [[Bahraini general election, 2014|2014 elections]]. However, the opposition maintained that the real voter turnout did not exceed 28%-30%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/12/record-number-bahraini-women-elected-parliament-181202165415224.html?|title=Record number of Bahraini women elected to parliament|website=www.aljazeera.com|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bahrainmirror.com/en/news/51115.html|title=Al-Wefaq Announces Failure of Elections: 30% Turnout at Most, Int’l Community Should Respect Bahraini People’s Will|publisher=|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20181126-bahrain-opposition-voter-turnout-did-not-exceed-30/|title=Bahrain opposition: Voter turnout did not exceed 30%|date=26 November 2018|publisher=|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref>
