{{dablink|Boar's Head redirects here. See also [[Boar's Head Provision Company]]. For the Shakespearean tavern see [[Boar's Head Inn]]}}
{{Multiple issues| {{Refimprove|date=January 2018}} {{Original research|date=January 2018}} }}
'''The Boar's Head Feast''' is a festival of the [[Christmastide|Christmas season]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2014}}
==History== ===In the U.S.=== [[Oglethorpe University]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] celebrates the Boar's Head Ceremony annually. "Boar's Head is held in the Conant Center on the first Friday in December. It begins with a procession of the members of [[Omicron Delta Kappa]], in academic regalia, carrying a roasted boar's head on a litter. The procession is followed by a reading of the Boar's Head story. The rest of the celebration consists of a concert featuring the University Singers and the Concert Winds, the lighting of the holiday tree and a reception sponsored by the Oglethorpe Student Association. The armorial crest of General James Edward Oglethorpe, which depicts four boars' heads, serves as the inspiration for this annual tradition".<ref>{{cite web|title=Glossary of Oglethorpe Terms and Historical References|url=http://www.oglethorpe.edu/about_us/oglethorpe_glossary.asp|publisher=Oglethorpe University|accessdate=22 May 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330211023/http://www.oglethorpe.edu/about_us/oglethorpe_glossary.asp|archivedate=30 March 2013|df=}}</ref>
=== University of Rochester === In 1934, the presidency of [[Benjamin Rush Rhees]] was waning and that of [[Alan Valentine]] was rising. Valentine, a [[Rhodes Scholarship|Rhodes Scholar]] at [[Balliol College, Oxford]], helped to solidify this tradition at Rochester <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usarugby.org/player/alan-valentine/|title=Alan Valentine|website=USA Rugby|access-date=2017-12-02}}</ref>. This American variant honors a professor and a club at the university each year hence <ref name="auto">{{Cite news|url=http://www.rochester.edu/newscenter/boars-head-dinner-goes-back-to-16th-century-for-one-night-285542/|title=Boar’s Head Dinner goes back to 16th century for one night|date=2017-12-01|work=NewsCenter|access-date=2017-12-02|language=en-US}}</ref>. The professor is responsible for the recounting of the tale of the boar, often at the expense of the students enrolled in their classes. The student club honored receives the head of the slain boar, the highest honor for that academic year. The feast has been held in numerous locations on the [[University of Rochester College of Arts Sciences and Engineering|River Campus]] and has settled into the newly refurbished Richard Feldman Ballroom <ref name="auto"/>.
Presentations of the Boar's Head festival can be found at: *Asylum Hill Congregational Church in Hartford, Connecticut * Bethlehem Lutheran Church in Saginaw, Michigan<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bethlehemsaginaw.org/#/whats-happening/boars-head-festival|title=Bethlehem Lutheran Church / Home / Welcome|author=|date=|website=bethlehemsaginaw.org|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> *Lutheran Church in St. Charles, Missouri<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.immanuelstcharles.org/cgi-bin/church.pl?fx1%3DBoars+Head+Participation+Form |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-10-31 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141031102209/http://www.immanuelstcharles.org/cgi-bin/church.pl?fx1=Boars%20Head%20Participation%20Form |archivedate=2014-10-31 |df= }}</ref> *Saint Paul United Methodist Church in Louisville, Kentucky *The First Church of Winsted in Winsted, Connecticut<ref>{{cite web|url=http://firstchurchofwinsted.org/BHfest.html|title=Boar's Head Festival|first=Debbie|last=STorrs|date=|website=firstchurchofwinsted.org|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref> *Third Presbyterian Church in Rochester, New York *Trinity Cathedral in Cleveland, Ohio *St. Peter's Lutheran Church in Lafayette Hill, Pennsylvania
